ing in a decrease in the diversity of the news. Peeking inside the newsrooms where journalists create stories and the work settings where the public reads them, Pablo J. Boczkowski reveals why journalists contribute to the growing similarity of news—even though they dislike it—and why consumers acquiesce to a media system they find increasingly dissatisfying. Comparing and contrasting two newspapers in Buenos Aires with similar developments in the United States, News at Work offers an enlightening perspective on living in a world with more information but less news.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNews audienceszArgentina. 0aOnline journalismzArgentina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aimitation, news, information age, headlines, internet, updates, journalism, argentina, buenos aires, digital media, consumption, distribution, production, technology, homogenous, print, commodity, capitalism, nonfiction, audience, competition, public affairs, consumer preference, sourcing, communication, mimicry, monitoring, reporting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022606279240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226062785423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226062785/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles